  "summary": "McCarty walks toward Misty's room, dismissively telling the narrator that he is a \"rational creature\" who has forgotten the concept of emotion. Later, around 10:30 p.m., Kajiya visits the narrator's room. They discuss Mrs. Hina, who is resting after the loss of the twins, Mutsu and Kiri. Kajiya, appearing sensitive and on edge, shares memories of his deceased mother. The narrator attempts to find a copy of the record \"Death and the Maiden\" to play for him, but it has gone missing. Kajiya then asks the narrator to protect the \"mist drawing,\" expressing a desire for redemption and a hope that \"that child\" is saved before he finds his own resting place.\n\nThe following morning, the body of the housekeeper, Yasuko, is discovered in her room behind the restaurant. Her severed head is placed on top of the previously missing \"Death and the Maiden\" record on a low table, while her body is discarded near the entrance. The narrator notes that unlike previous victims who were members of the Inagaki family, Yasuko was a servant, leading the inspector to suggest she may have known something unfavorable to the murderer. During the investigation, Chief Inspector Hatohara discovers an unremarkable engagement ring on Yasuko's right index finger. The ring is engraved with the Roman letters \"SHIITSUKI.\" Upon seeing this, the narrator exclaims that the housekeeper was actually \"Kurogane.\"",
